            "comments": [
                {
                    "file": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
                    "line": 0,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Joseph Reynolds",
                        "email": "joseph-reynolds@charter.net",
                        "username": "joseph-reynolds"
                    },
                    "message": "Work-in-progress.  This is a first-draft proposal for how to do security response, a followup to what we had discussed in the security working group (public) and the security response team (in private)."
                },
                {
                    "file": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
                    "line": 0,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "James Mihm",
                        "email": "James.Mihm@Intel.com",
                        "username": "JamesMihm"
                    },
                    "message": "Here are my review comments. Regarding #39, this is a broader issue that the TOF should help to resolve. I wanted to capture that this is a problem with the OpenBMC CVEs today."
                },
                {
                    "file": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
                    "line": 0,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Joseph Reynolds",
                        "email": "joseph-reynolds@charter.net",
                        "username": "joseph-reynolds"
                    },
                    "message": "Thanks for the comments.  I'll push updates to clarify."
                },
                {
                    "file": "security/obmc-security-response-team-guidelines.md",
                    "line": 39,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "James Mihm",
                        "email": "James.Mihm@Intel.com",
                        "username": "JamesMihm"
                    },
                    "message": "Since the project hasn't been doing official releases, using the OpenBMC Release is problematic. As it's not specific enough to track and isn't consistent. The better way to track the repositories is to start using repository versioning."
                },
                {
                    "file": "security/obmc-security-response-team-guidelines.md",
                    "line": 39,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Patrick Williams",
                        "email": "patrick@stwcx.xyz",
                        "username": "williamspatrick"
                    },
                    "message": "We still have tags made for releases.  Something from git-describe is still generally useful."
                },
                {
                    "file": "security/obmc-security-response-team-guidelines.md",
                    "line": 39,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Joseph Reynolds",
                        "email": "joseph-reynolds@charter.net",
                        "username": "joseph-reynolds"
                    },
                    "message": "In addition to the OpenBMC release described by https://github.com/openbmc/docs/blob/master/release/release-notes.md or by the git-describe command: the intention is for each openbmc application (per source repo) to have a semantic version, like 0.2.105.\n\nHaving a semantic version becomes important when using tools which scan the installable binary firmware image file.  Tools like blackduck decompose the file and analyze its readonly file system content.  For example, the tool detects which version of OpenSSL is present.  The tool then matches the OpenSSL package version against known vulnerabilities in that version and gives a report of the CVEs which might be in your firmware image.\n\nThe idea being proposed here is to use semantic versioning for all openbmc applications, to help security responders know which vulnerabilities are in their image."
                },
                {
                    "file": "security/obmc-security-response-team-guidelines.md",
                    "line": 39,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Patrick Williams",
                        "email": "patrick@stwcx.xyz",
                        "username": "williamspatrick"
                    },
                    "message": "> The idea being proposed here is to use semantic versioning for all openbmc applications, to help security responders know which vulnerabilities are in their image.\n\nThere is absolutely no words in this commit that convey this as an \"idea being proposed here\".  If that is your intention, please make sure it is reflected in the words you've written.\n\nWho is going to maintain that?  I have no interest in modifying the semantic version in each application on every commit.  I don't think repository maintainers are interested in taking on yet another manual operation.  Is this something we're just going to inject in the bitbake side of things?  If so, how would it map back to a commit in the repo?"
                },
                {
                    "file": "security/obmc-security-response-team-guidelines.md",
                    "line": 39,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Joseph Reynolds",
                        "email": "joseph-reynolds@charter.net",
                        "username": "joseph-reynolds"
                    },
                    "message": "Sorry, I was unclear.  I was responding to and expanding on the proposal in James' comment.  Upon further (private) discussion, we decided this is not the right place to ask each repo owner to add version numbers\nSNIP.\nSo, let's cut off this discussion, and:\n1. Ask problem responders to identify which version of their code is affected (such as a version# tag or a commitID in their repo).\n2. Re-start this discussion in some other forum, if desired."
                },
                {
                    "file": "security/obmc-security-response-team.md",
                    "line": 19,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "James Mihm",
                        "email": "James.Mihm@Intel.com",
                        "username": "JamesMihm"
                    },
                    "message": "The repository owners or maintainers create the security advisory. Using the term responders implies that the security response team may create the SA, but they don't have the proper permissions to do so."
                },
                {
                    "file": "security/obmc-security-response-team.md",
                    "line": 19,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Joseph Reynolds",
                        "email": "joseph-reynolds@charter.net",
                        "username": "joseph-reynolds"
                    },
                    "message": "I agree.  \"Responder\" should be: repo maintainer."
                }
            ],
